               HE that is adorned, and well furniſhed, with many and32 great vertues, although he be a very poore man, concerning this world, yet is he to be honored. For as pretious ſtones, though they be caſt into the mire, yet they loſe not their beautie, nature, and propertie: So men indued with honeſtie, repleniſhed with goodly vertues, and well acquainted with the true worſhipping, of the moſt high and gracious God, although they be ſilent, as men in their graues, and are had in contempt of the world, yet haue they not loſt their dignitie, and the true honor proper to Chriſtians, which conſiſteth not in the wealth and renowine of this world, but in holines, in righteouſnes, and in the faithfull imitation of Chriſt. Godly men are great men, though the world make no reckoning of them, and wickedmen, are vile and baſe men, although the world ſet and place them, in the heighth and top of all honor. Nothing is higher, nothing loftier, than vnfained vertue. There is nothing lower, nothing baſer, nothing 
