                  d without whom they were nothing but bond ſlaues of miſerie and wretchednes: but ſéeing they were like foule blacke cloudes, they were diſperſed, ſcattered, and vaniſhed away: And the glorie of Chriſt, againſt their wils, &amp; in ſpite of them, togither with the brightnes of his name, did break out, and ſhine abroad, and giue light throughout all the world. I would to God, that this ingratitude and vnthankfulnes, had neuer a corner in England, nor in any Engliſh hart: it hath pleaſed the almightie, by his faithfull ſeruant, Elizabeth, by his owne grace, Quéene of England, to deliuer our countrie from no leſſe bondage, thraldome and ſeruitude, than he did the Iſraelites by Moſes and Aaron: and yet we finde to too manie, that haue béen bred in England, and owe their liues to hir highnes, to murmure no leſſe againſt hir happines, than the Iſraelites did againſt the lords ſeruants Moſes and Aaron. The ſeruitude and ſlauerie of the Iſraelites, was not greater, nor woorſe vnder Pharao that tyrant in Egypt, than the bondage of England was vnder the Pope, neither ought we to be leſſe thankfull, for our deliuerie from the ſlauerie of Rome, than they ſhould haue béen, if they had well remembred themſelues, from the ſlauerie of Egypt. We read in the booke of Wiſdome, that the hope of theSapien. 16. vnthankfull man, ſhall waſte and conſume like winters ice, &amp;c. And t
